{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600520/1930121401/0453.xml":{"full_text":"B-10\nZEPPELIN FLEETS\nTO BE DISCUSSED\nAerial Merchant Marine Pro\nposal Debate Before U. S.\nAviation Leaders.\nThe status of Zeppelin airship de\nvelopment In the United States, leading\nup to the proposed creation of an\n\u201caerial merchant marine,\u201d will be dis\ncussed at a dinner meeting of the So\nciety of Automotive Engineers In the\nWashington Hotel at 6:30 p.m. tomor\nrow before aviation leaders of the Fed\neral Government.\nThe discussion will be lead by Or.\nKarl Arnstein, International authority\non dirigibles and vice president and\nchief engineer of the Goodyear Zeppelin\nCorporation, which now is engaged in\nthe construction of the world\u2019s greatest\nairships for the United States Navy.\nWilliam P. MacCracken, jr., former As\nsistant Secretary of Commerce for\nAeronautics, will be toastmaster.\nAmong the guests of honor will be\nDavid S. Ingalls. Assistant Secretary\nof the Navy for Aeronautics; Clarence\nV. Young, Assistant Secretary of Com\nmerce for Aeronautics W. Irving\nGlover, Second Assistant Postmaster\nGeneral in charge of airmail; MaJ. Gen.\nJames E. Fechet, chief of the Army Air\nCorps; Senator Hiram Bingham of Con\nnecticut, president of the National\nAeronautic Association; Capt John H.\nTowers, assistant chief of the Navy Bu\nreau of Aeronautics; Col. A. B. Barber,\nchief of the transportation division.\nUnited States Chamber of Commerce;\nDr. George W. Lewis, director of re\nsearch National Advisory Committee of\nAeronautics, and J. A. C. Warner, gen\neral manager of the Society of Auto\nmotive Engineers.\nA Preston Petre, former Navy officer\nand research engineer, will describe re\ncent progress in engine design and\nmanufacture. The dinner will be fol\nlowed by an entertainment program. C.\nS. Bruce of the Bureau of Standards,\nchairman of the Washington section of\nthe society, will preside. Arrangements\nare being made by j. C\u201e McCalmont,\nsecretary of the section.\nZIONISTS TO HONOR\nPALESTINE LEADER\nXenahem Uasishkin to Speak at\nJewish Community Center\nWednesday Night.\nThe combined Zionist organizations\nof Washington have arranged a mass\nmeeting Wednesday night in the Jewish\nCommunity Center In honor of Mena\nhem Usslshkin, president of the Jewish\nNational Fund and a resident of Jeru\nsalem, who is expected here Tuesday in\nthe course of an American tour in the\nInterest of the Jewish movement to\ncolonize Palestine. Mr. Usslshkin will\naddress the gathering on the subject of\n\"The Present Situation in Palestine\nand its Future Prospects.\u201d\nMr. Usslshkin made his home in\nPalestine In 1917 and soon afterward\nwas named head of the Zionist Com\nmission sent to Palestine under auspices\nof the British government. He is a\nnoted scholar, author on Jewish cul\ntural subjects, linguist and speaker of\nConsiderable ability.\nThe local committee in charge of ar\nrangements consists of B. Danzansky,\nchairman of National Fund Cbuncil of\nWashington; Louis Spiegler, president\nof Washington Zionist organization;\nMrs. Ann Alpher, president Hadajwh\nChapter; Maurice Garfinkle, president\nMixrachl Zionist organization of Wash\nington; Zalmon Hank in, representing\nPoale Zion organization: Mrs. John\nSafer, MT. Isadore Hershfleld. represent\ning the general Zionist organizations;\nRabbi J. T. Loeb, chairman Press Com\nmittee.\nGIRL TO WED FOR $5,000\nOffers to Be \u201cBusiness Depression\nBride\u201d for Payment.\nLOUIBVTLLE, Ky.. December 13 UP.\n\u2014Catherine Margaret Mary Nlchter, 18\nand pretty, of LouLsviUe. is willing to\nBecome a business depression bride in\n\u2022etum for $5,000.\nT win marry any man for $5,000,\u201d\nshe told the Louisville Times today,\n\"because my six small brothers and\nslaters are in great need. If there Is\nany man who is willing to nufrry me\nfor that sum I will be faithful to him\nfor the rest of ray life.\u201d\nMiss Nlchter said the family was in\ndanger of losing their cottage home\nbecause a bank closing had caused them\nto defaullt payments.\nCHILE PLANS U. S. BONDS\nProject to Finance $33,000,000\nPublic Works Budget.\nSANTIAGO, Chile. December 13 (A*).\n-Short-term bonds to be floated in the\nUnited States are expected to finance\na $53,000,000 public works budget which\nhas been laid down before Congress\nwith the request that It be adopted by\nthe end of the year. Service charges\non these bonds will be cared for by an\nIncrease in the tobacco tax and in\ncreased rgllroad earnings.\nThe ordinary budget, including the\nexpenditure for public works. totals\n1,816,348,158 pesos. or approximately\n$167,530.000\nHull, England, will erect a $9,000,000\nbridge over the Humber,\nThe Ease and Grace of Your Writing\nCan Tell Only One Thing\nSHEAFFER LIFETIME\nParker \u2014Carter \u2014W aterman\nThe Joy of Living Is in Having\nthe Beautiful Things in Life!\nBROWNIES\nmmm $2.50 to $5.00\nKODAKS\n$5.00 to $25.00\nBackgammon Board*. .$1 np Chess $1 up\nBackfamaon Seta.s2.sotos\u00df ss \u00abP\nPUymt Cards\u2014Poker Sets\n-Checker Boards 50c np Bill Folds $1 np\nWALFORD\u2019S\nEst. 1873 909 Pa. Ave. Na. 8039\nUTAH SENATOR S KNOWLEDGE\nOFFSETS LACK OF ORATORY\nSmoot Has Facts About\nGovernment From Every\nCorner.\nWagner Inquiry on Relief\nItem Reveals Preparedness\nfor Action.\nBY WILLIAM HARD.\nMr. Reed Smoot, a Senator of the\nUnited States from the State of Utah,\nwas at his best on the Senate floor last\nweek when an impassioned question was\nasked by Robert F. Wagner, a Sen\nator of the United States from the\nState of New York. Mr. Wagner was\ninspired by profound distrust of the\ngeneralizations contained in the un\nemployment relief bill. He exclaimed:\n\u201cIt is very easy to say that we will\nattempt to spend this money at once in\norder to relieve unemployment; but I\nthink we ought to know, if the informa\ntion is available, on what particular\nprojects operations will begin so as to\nemploy labor prior to six months from\nnow.\u201d\nMr. Wagner is a thick oak-trunk of\na man. He is also a rapidly rotating\nsteam-turbine of a man. He has solid\nity and he has power. He made his\nexclamation extremely energetic.\nWesley L. Jones, a Senator of the\nUnited States from the State of Wash\nington, was quite non-committal in his\nreply to Mr. Wagner. Mr. Jones was\nin charge of the bill. He has a long\nline of legislative accomplishments in\nhis record. He is no mean legislator,\nunless the Jones flve-and-ten liquor\nlambasting law was mean. Mr. Jones,\nnevertheless, in spite of his legislative\naptitudes and experiences, stared at Mr.\nWagner perplexed. He began replying\nwith \u201cI cannot tell\u201d and finished with\nintimating that he seemed to remember\nthat the projects for the deepening of\nrivers and harbors had ben set forth on\nthe witness stand by the War Depart\nment\u2019s chief of engineers.\nFacts on Fatted Calf.\nThen Mr. Smoot intervened. What\nhe said was characteristic of a thousand\ninterventions he has made in senatorial\ndebate. He said:\n\u201cI have the projects listed before me\nand, if the Senator so desires, will men\ntion them.\u201d\nThat\u2019s the way it always seems to\nbe. After the Senate has talked for\ntwo or three days about whether or\nnot a fatted calf should be killed and\nabout whether it should be boiled or\nbroiled or roasted, somebody thinks of\ninquring:\n\u201cBut where, after all, is the calf?\"\nThen Mr. Smoot rises and says:\n\u201cI know where the calf is, and he\nnow weighs 732 pounds.\u201d\n\u201cBut where is he?\u201d persists the in\nquirer.\nThen Mr. Smoot\u2014not always\u2014but\nusually\u2014says in effect:\n\u201cWell, he\u2019s tethered in my office.\"\nThus, on the specific occasion here\nnarrated, Mr. Smoot was able to in\nform the Senate, out of the careful\ncalculations kept close to his person,\nthat the proposed expenditure on the\nMiddle River and empire cut In Califor\nnia would be $3,000, while the expendi\nturc on the Ketchikan Creek in Alaska\nWOMAN WILL DISCUSS\nOPPORTUNITY CREED\nProblems of Those Threatened\nWith Lots of Work to Come\nBefore Today\u2019s Tea.\nProblems of women threatened with\nloss of work will be discussed at a tea\nof the National Woman\u2019s Party this\nafternoon from 4:30 to 6 in the head\nquarters, 144 B street northeast. The\nmeeting will be open to the public.\nConsideration will be given to the\nrecent action of a conference on\nwomen in industry, conducted by the\nparty in Philadelphia. The organiza\ntion\u2019s attitude was expressed at tha:\ntimes as follows:\n1. We affirm that at this time of un\nemployment, no woman, married or\nsingle, now employed, shall be requires\nto give up her job to a man.\n2. That women\u2019s opportunity for work\nshould not be limited by dismissing them\nfrom night work. The taking away of\nwomen\u2019s work does not Improve their\nhealth.\n3. That for any one to arrogate to\nhimself the right to limit women\u2019s work\nimplies the assumption of the Inferior\nity of women to men; a doctrine we\nresent\n4. That any attempt to carry out a\nplan of dismissal of women, either\nthrough legislation or by regulation, will\nbe opposed by the National Woman's\nParty\n5. That this present treatment of\nemployed women necessitates the im\nmediate passage of the equal rights\namendment which declares that \u201cmen\nand women shall have equal rights\nthroughout the United States and every\nplace subject to its jurisdiction.\u201d\nCOLOMBIANS GET JAZZ\nCUCUTA. Colombia OS*).\u2014Out here in\nthe heart of the Andes, four days\u2019 Jour\nney from Bogota, the natives don\u2019t\nstrum their guitars any more. They\u2019d\nrather hear New York jazz.\nRadio is the answer. Not that any\nI Individual would go to the expense of\nbuying a set. but the town has one. and\n11 there is a big loud speaker at each of\nthe public squares.\nthe stryrDAY star. Washington,, d. c\u201e December %4. 1930\u2014 part one.\nSENATOR SMOOT.\nwould be $272,000 and that on the\nLittle Machlpongo River in Virginia\nwould be SIO,OOO.\nGets Out and Dusts.\nMr. Smoot is said to consist of dust.\nThat is not the right way of putting\nit. It should rather be said that Mr.\nSmoot is a great hand to get out and\ndust. While others orate, he looks be\nhind the pictures and under the rugs\nand back of the radiators in the\nFederal Government and he returns to\nthe Senate floor with more knowledge\nof the Federal Government\u2019s recesses\nand of their contents than perhaps any\nother Senator has ever had in the\nSenate\u2019s whole history.\nThe President\u2019s Emergency Employ\nment Committee, headed by Col. Arthur\nWoods of New York, is now engaged in\ntrying to abbreviate the nine months\nwhich customarily elapse between a\nFederal choosing of a site for a Federal\nbuilding and a shoving of a spade into\nthe ground on that site for the ultimate\nerection of the building. Oratory\nagainst that nine months has been\nvoluminous on Capitol Hill. Col. Woods\nand his aides were able easily to col\nlect big baskets of criticisms of the de\nlays producing the nine months. What,\nthough, produced the delays them\nselves? What were the methods, what\nthe situations, that made the delays\nactually in practice occur?\nMr. Smoot knew. He knew about\nthere being only one Site Selection\nCommittee in the whole Federal Gov\nernment and about the congestion\nthereupon of site selection proposals in\nthat committee\u2019s hands.\nMany Things He Knows.\nHe knew about the legislative author\ni ization to the Treasury Department to\ni employ outside engineering help for\nbuilding plans but not for building\nj specifications. He knew about the de\nj termination of the controller general\neral of the United States to scrutinize\nthe titles to sites for perhaps many\nweeks after the Attorney General ct\nthe United States in the course of per\nhaps also many weeks had approved\nthe titles. Mr. Smoot knew every\ndreary spoke on this large and laborious\nwheel. He knew it legislatively and he\nknew it administratively. He knows'\neverything in Washington that would\nbore Borah.\nMr. Smoot is now engaged with the\nexperts of Col. Wood\u2019s committee in\nthinking out ways whereby the bureau\ncratic preliminaries of Federal building\nconstruction may be shortened irom\nnine months to eight, seven, six. If we\nget our Federal buildings more prompt\nly. we shall owe our happiness in a\nhigh degree to Mr. Smoot. If, though,\nhe should ever (and he won\u2019t) drate\nabout it on the Senate floor, the Sen\nate \u2014and the Senate press gallery,\ntoo\u2014would fall asleep. He orates like\nI dust\n(Copyright 1330.\nr l TW\u00bb th f, Ri\u00ab\ni\\ 1\nm U uin January \\1\nMl Usually HeW 1\nGreatest Reductions of All\nTime on Our Fine Stock of\nFAMOUS\nDOUBLEWEAR\nand 2 Pants\nSUITS\nOVERCOATS\n2 Feature Groups:\nFormerly up to S4O Formerly up to $55\nReduced to Reduced to\n*23* 33*\nFormer SBS\nWORUMBO OVERCOATS\nReduced to sy|{Vso\nTwo handsome shades-\u2014a rich\nCamel Tan and a smart Mist Gray. JL h/\nFRED PELZMAN\u2019S\n\u00a9aWaiSltcp\n9th E STS.\u2014SOI NINTH ST.\nNEW YORK REDS\nROUTED BY POLICE\nAttempt to Carry Banners,\nDenouncing France and\nU. S., Past Consulate.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, December 13.\u2014Uptown\nFifth avenue, with its Christmas shop\npers and elite traffic, was the scene of\nriot and struggle, Jeers and cheers for\nnearly an hour today as several hun\ndred Communists attempted to carry\nbanners of denunciation past the\nFrench consulate in East Fortieth\nstreet.\nThe demonstration was an outgrowth\nof the recent treason trials in Soviet\nRussia, at which it was charged other\npowers were plotting against Russia.\nThe call, printed in the Dally Worker,\nCommunist organ, declared it would be\n\u201cthe workers\u2019 answer to the Imperial\nists of France in the United States.\u201d\nThe red column reached a point be\ntween Fifth avenue and thq consulate\nwhen a handful of police charged, using\nclub 6 and fists and tearing down the\nsigns.\nDriven back to Fifth avenue, reds\nagain lifted their banners and broke\ninto song. Traffic clogged as the street\nfilled with crowds of curious. Fights\nbetween bystanders and Communists\nbroke out.\nAugmented squads of police charged\nagain and split the Communists into\ntwo groups. But the Communists\nunited again and were attacked again.\nEach time they fell back Into the crowd,\nonly to emerge holding their tattered\nbanners aloft.\nReserve police swung into the ave\nnue and for the next 20 minutes the\nreds were driven back and forth across\nthe street. Here and there a woman\nattacked a policeman.\nLocating the main body of the Com\nmunists in the large crowd, the officers\nchanged their tactics and drove them to\nForty-first street by forming a line and\nusing no violence. Gradually the radi\ncals melted into the shopping crowd\nand the riot was over.\nSeveral arrests were made.\nM\u2019LEAN SETTLEMENT\nOUT OF COURT SOUGHT\nWife of Publisher Asking SIO,OOO\nMonthly for Support of Children\nand Self.\nEfforts of opposing counsel to settle\nout of court the suit of Mrs. Edward\nBeale McLean, wife of the publisher\nof the Washington Post, were evident\nyesterday when counsel for Mrs. Mc-\nLean confirmed the report that efforts\nto subpoena Mr. McLean in the case had\nbeen abandoned.\nMrs. McLean is suing her husband for\nSIO,OOO a month support for herself\nand her three children.\nJohn J. Clarkson, Deputy United\nStates marshal, wh ohas held a sub\npoena for M/ McLean since the filing\nof the suit, has been notified to abandon\nefforts to serve the papers, and with\nthis Information as the basis, reports\nwere current yesterday that counsel are\nconsidering a private agreement to pre\nvent the case coming to trial in Dis\ntrict Supreme Court.\nMan Found Asphyxiated.\nDENVER, December 13 (4 s ).\u2014The\nbody of William J. Carter, real estate\nand theater man, was found in a garage\nin the rear of his home today.\nDeath was caused by carbon monox\nide asphyxiation.\nGERMANY BLOCKS\nSUGARAGREEMENT\nAll Rest of Europe Ready to\nAccept Cuban-American\nPlan.\nBy the Associated Press.\nBRUSSELS, December 13.\u2014An agree\nment on a plan to stabilize what\nThomas L. Chadbourne called \u201ca be\nwitched industry\"\u2014the world's sugar\nbusiness\u2014was reached today by all\nContinental European nationals attend\ning the International Sugar Conference,\nexcept Germany,\nThus the conference must continue\nMonday.\nOther Delegates Agree.\nBecause Germany refused the pro\nposed radical reduction in her exports\nthe other European delegations con\nferred without them today and decided\non the reduction each was willing to\nmake to fit in with the plan of Mr.\nChadbourne, head of the Cuban-\nAmerican Sugar Commission.\nIn a brief talk to the European dele\ngates Mr. Chadbourne indicated his\ndisappointment at the failure to reach\na unanimous accord.\nHe told the delegates that if the\nconference fell through, Continental\nEurope this year would not market 80\nper cent of the sugar it did last year.\n\u201cHow can you possibly?\u201d Chadbourne\nasked. \u201cWe have 1,500,000 tons of\nsugar to put where we want at what\nprice we want. The Dutch have 500,000\ntons to market where they want at\nwhat price they want. It just can\u2019t\nbe done, gentlemen.\u201d\nStatement Bouses Discussion.\nThere was much discussion of this\nstatement, some interpreting it to\nmean that if the Europeans did not\nreach an agreement the allied Dutch\nand Cuban-American interests would\ndump great quantities of sugar in their\ncountries and force them to come to\nterms.\nBermuda Badio Planned.\nNEW YORK, December 13 (/P).\u2014The\nAmerican Telephone Telegraph Co\nhas asked the Federal Radio Commis\nsion for a permit to erect stations for\na short-wave radio telephone service\nbetween the United States and Ber\nmuda. The American plant would be\nat Lawrencevllle, N. J.\nSTAR RADIO CO\n409 11th St. N. W. 3218 14th St. N. W. 1350 F St N. W.\nWashington's Largest Radio Stores\nSELECT YOUR\nRADIOLA\nf\nFrom Our Complete Stock\nO pm _\nCome to the Star Radio Store nearest j||\nto your home and inspect the com- j|j fO\nplete line of Radiolas now on display. j|| Wn|H\nSAVE AT THE \u201cSTAR\u201d 11 23 E\ni: V hl(h quality acr\u00bben grid radio fjVJB\nin RCA Radiol, history. ff'M\nLIBERAL ALLOWANCE p B|B\nFOR YOUR OLD RADIO i\nLowest Finance Charges i I\nf\u00abM Radio tro*\u00bb I /jA\ni'i A 8166.00 Complete ?jj|\nModel 80\u2014S up r-Heterodyne. a\nLONGEST TERMS 1 i\nFREE DELIVERY Ifil 13 1'\nFREE INSTALLATION 1 JsSSs.\nModel 88\u2014-Super-Heterodyne hi 9 s\ncombination with newest elec\nin?i?it Qwx/ir'u m ph gy\ni m\\this oJlLix v Ik*E* \u2018voi\".* 11 r cord ot rouT own K1\nCad| Delivers a Radiola to yogr |t|\nI home. No more to pay until fe JSi rS\n8308.00 Complete frX\nlannoMi Model 80 \u2014a marvaloua etr- bCv\nJanuary. S'* cu lt Super-Heterolyne, with too. <Rg\nJ ism er eantrol. Exqui.tt.ly fie- kJC\ngg| <ahad W,l Ut T r cabtn#t\nMILK DELIVERY AUTO\nLACKS \u201cHORSE SENSE\u201d\nDriver Crashes When Machine\nto Travel Route When He\nGoes to Sleep at Wheel.\nBy the Associated Preai.\nHAMMOND, Ind., December 13.\nJupiter\u2019s brief holiday is over and he\u2019s\ngoing back to work, if Raymond Thiel,\na milkman, has his way. At least that's\nthe understanding of the Hammond Po\nlice Department.\nJupe.\" said Thiel, as he sat in the\nmidst of the wreckage of an automo\nbile which had been substituted for\nFOR SALE OR RENT\u2014This Attractive Home on Tilden Street\n.lust East of Connecticut Avenue.\nthe beautiful entrance to Rock Greek Park and facing Pierce\u2019s Mill you will see\nthis attractive Colonial home, having a picturesque setting on Tilden street hill.\nd e a bedrooms and ideal appointments; large lawn, having beautiful shade trees and inclosed with t\nw *L\u00b0 n n w This restricted location is substantially developed with elegant homes and its commanding view of\nthe Park valley gives a charming atmosphere and makes it a most desirable situation.\nApply to E. S. NEWMAN, Owner, No. 2600 Tilden St.\nJupiter and which had Just made con\ntact with a telephone pole, \"knew all\nthe customers and he would always stop\nIn the right places. Along about sun\nrise the Job would be done. All 1 had\nto do after that was to twist the reins\naround the whip socket and go to sleep.\nJupe would take me safely home.\n\"An automobile may be a fine con\ntraption. but It won't take a sleeping\ndriver home safely. It hasn\u2019t got\nenough horse sense.\u201d\nDeclines College Presidency.\nNASHVILLE. Tenn.. Dec. 13 (A*).\u2014\nDr. John L. Hill, book editor of the\nSunday School Board of the Southern\nBaptist Convention, today declined the\npresidency of Georgetown (Ky.) Col\nlege, to which he was elected Thursday.\nEARLY PAY FOR TEACHERS\nAtlanta Oflcials Arrange for\nChecks Before Christmas.\nATLANTA, Ge\u201e December 13\nAtlanta school teachers will have a lot\nof extra spending money this Christ\nmas. but It will be Just that much\nlonger between pay days.\nCity officials were arranging today %t>\npay the teachers before Christmas In\nstead of January l. a department\nstore offered to handle the financing,\nestimating It would add $350,000 to the\nholiday trade.\nMore than 9,000 persons now are em\nployed In the British asbestos Industry.","height":"25536","width":"19740"}}
